It’s been a year since Russia’s full-scale invasion of #Ukraine. Millions of people have been forced to flee their homes, and an estimated 17 million people need urgent humanitarian assistance.

I’m proud to support @internationalmedicalcorps and their lifesaving work in Ukraine.

Over the last year, International Medical Corps has reached 5.8 million people in Ukraine, Poland and Moldova with emergency medical relief and supplies, including clean water, stoves, generators and more, as well as health, mental health and protection services under increasingly difficult and dangerous conditions.

Please share this video and give what you can. Your support will help more people get the care they so urgently need.  Together, we can make a difference for people whose lives have been devastated by war. https://bit.ly/Ukraine-1Year

 

#StandWithUkraine

#IMC

#internationalmedicalcorps

OK I’m obsessed with my trainer, Renata. I’ve been working out with her on FORME for the last 7 months. I thought it would be weird to workout with a trainer virtually because I’ve only ever trained with a human person in a gym. But she’s become my friend, my therapist, my boss, my fellow dog lover and, oh yeah, my trainer. We’d never met in person until last week when we both happened to be in New York. So we trained IRL together! It was so fun! We wandered all over Central Park pretending we were in the opening scene of a Law & Order SVU episode (which we both love.) AND THEN LOOK WHO SHE MET LATER THAT NIGHT!! I’m convinced we summonsed him. With great power comes great responsibility. 

Love sweating with you @renatacmoleta and @thisisformelife

I’m honored to announce that I’m officially a Global Ambassador for @internationalmedicalcorps! I’ve been a supporter of this amazing nonprofit since 2017, when I saw them hard at work in Puerto Rico after Hurricane Maria, a devastating Category 5 storm. They believe that access to lifesaving healthcare is a human right (agreed!), and their mission is to save lives and relieve suffering by providing medical relief and support to communities around the world that are affected by war, disaster and disease. They also help people and communities become self-reliant by providing training. I’m so beyond thrilled to be working with them!! 

Please join me in supporting their #humanitarian work in Ukraine and around the world. Follow them and find out more at their website: www.InternationalMedicalCorps.org.

#internationalmedicalcorps #nonprofit #medicalrelief #globalnonprofit

The spotted seal gets its name from its coat pattern, which is usually a light-colored background with dark spots. Spotted seals are widely distributed on the continental shelf of the Beaufort, Chukchi, southeastern East Siberian, Bering, and Okhotsk Seas; south through the Sea of Japan; and into the northern Yellow Sea. From late fall through spring, spotted seal habitat use is primarily associated with seasonal sea ice. Most spotted seals spend the rest of the year making periodic foraging trips from haul-out sites onshore or on sea ice. Spotted seals are unusual among true seals in that they annually form “family” groups consisting of a female, a male, and a pup during breeding season.
